<div type="definition">
<p>SMALL in the MORE SMALL DIMENSION.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The current general word for narrowness is xiá 狹 (ant. kuān 寬 "broad") which refers quite generally to the small size of any opening.</p>
<p>2. Ài 隘 typically, but not always, connotes difficult military access.</p>
<p>3. Lòu 陋 (ant.* kuò 闊 "in grand style") refers only indirectly to narrowness of a street as an indication of its undistinguished character. The word focusses on this undistinguished character and is quite marginal in this group.</p>
        </div>
<div type="modern-chinese-criteria">
<p>狹隘</p>
<p>狹窄</p>
<p>窄小</p>
<p>狹小</p>
<p>窄</p>
<p>狹</p>
<p>小</p>
<p>rough draft to BEGIN TO identify synonym group members for analysis, based on CL etc. 18.11.2003. CH ／</p>
